<subSubSection lastPageId="14" lastPageNumber="97" pageId="13" pageNumber="96" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="13.[674,1212,755,1700]" box="[677,821,755,781]" pageId="13" pageNumber="96">DESCRIPTION</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="13.[674,1212,755,1700]" pageId="13" pageNumber="96">
<materialsCitation collectionCode="L, H, W" pageId="13" pageNumber="96" specimenCount="1" typeStatus="paratype">
Shell of medium size, specimens on hand ranging from about 
<quantity box="[800,877,818,844]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.5" pageId="13" pageNumber="96" unit="mm" value="25.0">25 mm</quantity>
in length to 
<quantity box="[1007,1105,818,844]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.81" pageId="13" pageNumber="96" unit="mm" value="58.1">58.1 mm</quantity>
(
<typeStatus box="[1117,1210,818,844]" pageId="13" pageNumber="96">paratype</typeStatus>
4). Rather elongate (
<collectionCode box="[901,919,850,876]" pageId="13" pageNumber="96">L</collectionCode>
/ 
<collectionCode box="[928,949,850,876]" pageId="13" pageNumber="96">H</collectionCode>
range 0.76-0.91, mean 0.83) and moderately inflated (
<collectionCode box="[986,1012,882,908]" pageId="13" pageNumber="96">W</collectionCode>
/ 
<collectionCode box="[1021,1038,882,908]" pageId="13" pageNumber="96">L</collectionCode>
range 0.65-0.90, mean 0.76). Shell never oblique, almost symmetrical
</materialsCitation>
; posterior margin always curved, never truncated.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="13.[674,1212,755,1700]" pageId="13" pageNumber="96">Lunular area narrow, slightly hollowed, with margins somewhat raised along entire extent.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="13.[674,1212,755,1700]" pageId="13" pageNumber="96">External colour uniformly yellow; internal shell coloration white.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="13.[674,1212,755,1700]" pageId="13" pageNumber="96">
Hinge characteristic of the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Vidal" authorityYear="1999" class="Bivalvia" family="Cardiidae" genus="Acrosterigma" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cardiida" pageId="13" pageNumber="96" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="uniornatum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="96">Acrosterigma uniornatum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species group (
<bibRefCitation author="VIDAL J." box="[878,1057,1135,1161]" pageId="13" pageNumber="96" pagination="259 - 335" refId="ref18457" refString="VIDAL J. 1999. - Taxonomic review of the elongated cockles: genera Trachycardium, Vasticardium and Acrosterigma (Mollusca, Cardiidae). Zoosystema 21 (2): 259 - 335." type="journal article" year="1999">Vidal 1999: 271</bibRefCitation>
), with a rather symmetrical, moderately angled (A = 122-130°, see 
<figureCitation box="[675,756,1199,1225]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="4.[113,124,1455,1472]" captionTargetBox="[685,1153,294,1385]" captionTargetId="graphics-16@4.[776,1075,612,983]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIG. 2.— Morphometrics used in this study to differentiate cardiid taxa:A, delineates height (H) and length (L) measurements;B, external shell regions PT1, PT2 (typical of Pseudofulvia n. gen.); C, width (W); D, angle A, the angle formed by the most dorsal cardinal and laterals;E, I, the lunular heart and II, the lunular area (typical of Fulvia); F, I, the lunule s.s. and II, the lunular area (typical of Ctenocardia). For A, B, D the left valve is figured. Refer to Materials and methods for further description of these terms, see also Vidal (1994)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5401698" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5401698/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="96">Fig. 2D</figureCitation>
) hinge and cardinals connected in the right valve by a shallow saddle.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="13.[674,1212,755,1700]" box="[699,827,1262,1288]" pageId="13" pageNumber="96">Ribs 42-47.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="13.[674,1212,755,1700]" lastBlockId="14.[112,648,470,718]" lastPageId="14" lastPageNumber="97" pageId="13" pageNumber="96">
Posterior half of shell with a similar arrangement of oblique scales on top and posterior side of individual ribs. Ornamentation of the posterior slope may contrast with that of the medio-posterior slope, the axial furrow on the posterior ribs, generally present in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Dall" authorityYear="1900" box="[792,924,1452,1478]" class="Bivalvia" family="Cardiidae" genus="Acrosterigma" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cardiida" pageId="13" pageNumber="96" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[792,924,1452,1478]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="96">Acrosterigma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but absent in this species group can be sporadically present, with sessile, oblique scales less numerous and more tubercular (
<figureCitation box="[684,761,1547,1573]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="12.[113,124,1634,1651]" captionTargetBox="[187,1140,215,1526]" captionTargetId="figure-15@12.[187,1140,198,1559]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIG. 4. — A-C, Pseudofulvia caledonica n. gen., n. sp.; D-F, P. arago n. gen., n. sp.; G-J, Acrosterigma capricorne n. sp.; I, highlighting detail of posterior and medio-posterior zones of left valve; J, highlighting medio-zones, with no herringbone structures in central region. Scale bars: 5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5401702" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5401702/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="96">Fig. 4I</figureCitation>
). The first ribs of the posterior zone, and the last ribs of the median zone can bear short scales on the anterior flank of the ribs, forming an asymmetrical chevron-like structure together with the longer top and posterior scales. These anterior scales progressively disappear towards the anterior and the posterior, where the scales shorten and become limited to the posterior flank of the ribs (
<figureCitation box="[171,272,565,591]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="12.[113,124,1634,1651]" captionTargetBox="[187,1140,215,1526]" captionTargetId="figure-15@12.[187,1140,198,1559]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIG. 4. — A-C, Pseudofulvia caledonica n. gen., n. sp.; D-F, P. arago n. gen., n. sp.; G-J, Acrosterigma capricorne n. sp.; I, highlighting detail of posterior and medio-posterior zones of left valve; J, highlighting medio-zones, with no herringbone structures in central region. Scale bars: 5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5401702" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5401702/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="97">Fig. 4I, J</figureCitation>
). On the medio-anterior slope the posterior scales appear on the anterior flank of the ribs, forming a herringbone structure. These angled scales become progressively curved, low-rounded ornaments on the anterior slope.
</paragraph>
