<paragraph blockId="14.[111,647,755,1098]" box="[113,278,755,781]" pageId="14" pageNumber="97">MICROHABITAT</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="14.[111,647,755,1098]" pageId="14" pageNumber="97">
Found in depths from 
<quantity box="[359,484,787,813]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.15" metricValueMax="13.5" metricValueMin="0.8" pageId="14" pageNumber="97" unit="m" value="715.0" valueMax="1350.0" valueMin="80.0">80-1350 m</quantity>
. Recently dead material found at the shallowest depth, with older shells found at deeper depth. This indicates that 
<taxonomicName authority="Vidal &amp; Kirkendale, 2007" authorityName="Vidal &amp; Kirkendale" authorityYear="2007" box="[115,250,882,908]" class="Bivalvia" family="Cardiidae" genus="Acrosterigma" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cardiida" pageId="14" pageNumber="97" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="capricorne" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis box="[115,130,882,908]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="97">A</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[144,250,882,908]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="97">capricorne</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[257,317,882,908]" pageId="14" pageNumber="97" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
may live at the shallow end of this depth range, and be transported down slope 
<emphasis box="[113,239,945,971]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="97">post mortem</emphasis>
. However, this species, like other taxa in the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Vidal" authorityYear="1999" box="[178,433,977,1003]" class="Bivalvia" family="Cardiidae" genus="Acrosterigma" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cardiida" pageId="14" pageNumber="97" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="uniornatum">
<emphasis box="[178,433,977,1003]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="97">Acrosterigma uniornatum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species group (
<bibRefCitation author="VIDAL J." pageId="14" pageNumber="97" pagination="259 - 335" refId="ref18457" refString="VIDAL J. 1999. - Taxonomic review of the elongated cockles: genera Trachycardium, Vasticardium and Acrosterigma (Mollusca, Cardiidae). Zoosystema 21 (2): 259 - 335." type="journal article" year="1999">Vidal 1999: 271</bibRefCitation>
), is really generally found at greater depth than most other 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lamarck" authorityYear="1809" box="[286,391,1040,1066]" class="Bivalvia" family="Cardiidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cardiida" pageId="14" pageNumber="97" phylum="Mollusca" rank="family">Cardiidae</taxonomicName>
(except Protocardiinae) in the western Pacific.
</paragraph>
